{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4823537c-c3d7-437e-a7b5-cde3adba73c7","content":"Your project isn't present in this workspace, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the most common for local servers):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your server must read JSON-RPC from stdin and write responses to stdout (the `ModelContextProtocol` / `McpServer` NuGet packages handle this).\n- **Don't** write logs to stdout — use stderr instead, or they'll corrupt the protocol stream.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary, replace `dotnet run --project ...` with the path to the executable.\n\nIf your server uses **SSE/HTTP** transport instead, use:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"sse\",\n      \"url\": \"http://localhost:5000/sse\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nAfter saving, open the VS Code command palette → **MCP: List Servers** to verify it's detected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b9f13c84-0724-498c-ba52-87bf04dc3173","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but the user says they built it. They're just asking for configuration guidance. Let me provide the mcp.json configuration.","outputTokens":418,"requestId":"5037:1DFA19:DA54B7:FA5E5B:69F2AB6D"},"id":"1b3c4eb2-29aa-492f-91c8-938a79174f65","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:08:08.242Z","parentId":"6192fd83-8f5a-450d-8828-c9565618286a"}
